Note: A monthly COGS of ~$17.00 is high for a standard $20/mo SaaS subscription. The "Scout" is the cost driver.
7.2 Monetization Strategy: Outcome-Based & Hybrid Pricing

To align revenue with costs and value, Genio must adopt a Hybrid Pricing Model.  

7.2.1 Tiered Subscription (Base Layer)

    "The Reader" ($20/mo): Includes the Librarian (unlimited ingest) and "Lite Scout" (Vector-only search, no Deep Research loops). Covers the base platform costs.

7.2.2 "Agent Credits" (Compute Layer)

    "The Scholar" (Add-on): Users purchase "Cognitive Credits" for Deep Scout usage.

        1 Deep Research Loop = 1 Credit (~$0.10 cost to user).

        This caps the downside risk for Genio while allowing power users (e.g., a PhD student doing a literature review) to scale their usage as needed.

7.2.3 Outcome-Based Pricing (Enterprise)

For B2B clients (Think Tanks, R&D Labs), Genio sells "Completed Research Briefs."

    Product: "Scout, generate a 50-page comparative analysis of these 200 PDFs."

    Price: $50 per Brief.

    Value: Replaces 10+ hours of analyst time.

    Margin: High. (Cost to generate might be $5 in tokens; Price is $50).

8. Conclusion: The Blueprint for 2026

The Genio Knowledge OS represents the transition from Information Retrieval to Knowledge Construction. By 2026, the technology exists to build this:

    LCMs allow us to map the logical structure of books, not just index their words.

    GraphRAG allows us to maintain a coherent, evolving memory of the user's worldview.

    Agentic Orchestration allows the system to proactively scout the horizon, bringing back the "Deltas" that drive learning.

This architecture solves the Activation Energy problem by offloading the structural overhead of reading to the AI. It solves the Information Silo problem by deploying an autonomous agent whose sole purpose is to find the connections the user cannot see. It is a tool for the "Active Mind," designed not just to consume information, but to master it.
